  "text": "A pounding heart at the top of hill sprints is your heart doing its job; maximal efforts push heart rate near its ceiling and it feels dramatic, especially if the reps were harder or the day hotter than usual. Lifting today is fine. You logged 394 minutes of sleep, about 6.6 hours, which is on the shorter side, and since you're logging manually I have no heart rate, HRV, or recovery data to lean on, so let perceived effort set the load and keep a rep or two in reserve on big lifts. Worth knowing the boundary: pounding during an all-out effort that settles as you recover is normal, while a racing or irregular heartbeat at rest, fluttering out of nowhere, or pounding with chest pain or lightheadedness is different and worth getting checked.",
